What is Happening?
As part of a combination of both industry changes and Mastercard’s focus on providing highly reliable, performant and secure solutions there are several important changes planned in 2026 that may affect your current integration.
DNS Changes
The DNS changes will move from static records that map IP addresses to hostnames on a one-to-one basis to rotating DNS records across multiple IP addresses to enable greater flexibility in traffic routing for availability and performance optimization.
Beginning July 1, 2026, our Payment Gateway services will commence a series of updates to the Domain Name System (DNS) configuration strategy for internet-facing endpoints and the currently supported Transport Layer Security (TLS) cipher lists. These enhancements are part of our ongoing efforts to improve security and resiliency in accordance with current industry best practices.
PKI Root Certificate Authority Changes
From 30 June 2026, major browsers will enforce changes to TLS certificate issuing practices which will result in certificates currently used for authentication to be unable to be renewed as the authorities are mandating separation between client authentication and service identification issuing chains. As a result, all current Root Certificate Authorities for client certificates used to authenticate to the PKI interface will stop supporting the signing of the Client Authentication “Extended Key Usage” attribute and alternative issuing roots will need to be adopted.
Certificate providers have already stopped adding this flag to new certificates or renewals by default and plan to cease signing entirely by Q2 2026. Merchants should check with their chosen certificate provider for specific timelines.
To maintain support for the current authentication mechanism, Mastercard has reviewed available public issuing options and approved the following certificate authorities who are offering client authentication as an ongoing solution to be trusted issuers for merchants to transition to.
•	Digicert - DigiCert Assured ID Client CA G2
•	GlobalSign - GlobalSign Client Authentication Root R45
•	SSL.COM - SSL.com Client RSA Root CA 2022 & SSL.com Client ECC Root CA 2022
Please be advised that Mastercard will continue to assess additional emerging options and will communicate further details when they become available.
Merchants should check the expiry dates of their current certificates and either arrange an early renewal with the client authentication flag enabled through their supplier or start planning a move to one of the listed alternate Root Certificate Authorities before the certificate expires.
For merchants whose certificates expire after 30 June 2026, Mastercard will support those certificates until their expiry date or 30 June 2027, whichever comes first. After that, merchants must transition to one of the nominated alternate issuing authorities listed above.
Transport Layer Security Cipher Changes
In alignment with current best practice security standards, supported cipher lists are regularly reviewed to remove weaker ciphers from service whenever possible when not constrained by widespread customer or consumer usage.
Please note that the exact TLS ciphers negotiable will vary depending on whether TLSv1.2 or TLSv1.3 protocol is used on the connection.
What do you need to do?
It is strongly recommended that you promptly engage your system administrator or network team, as they possess the necessary expertise to make the required changes below to your system configuration. Their involvement will ensure that any updates to DNS settings, firewall rules, access control lists, or TLS cipher suites are implemented correctly and securely. Your collaboration with your IT specialists will also help minimise downtime and prevent any inadvertent disruption to your services during this process. It is recommended not to make these changes unless you have the relevant technical knowledge and authorisation, as improper configuration could compromise the security or accessibility of your systems.
